Also, by using scatter and hexbin diagrams, we can check the correlation of features in a more detailed way.

In [101]:
for feature in list(corr_bests.index)[1:5]:
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, figsize=(5, 10))
    axes[0].scatter(df[feature], df["price"])
    axes[0].set_title(feature + " scatter")
    
    axes[1].hexbin(df[feature], df["price"], gridsize=20, cmap='Blues')
    axes[1].set_title(feature + " hexbin")

  • scatter plot displays the relationship between two variables as a set of points on a two-dimensional coordinate system. Each point represents an observation in the dataset, where the x-axis corresponds to one variable and the y-axis corresponds to the other variable. The position of each point on the plot represents the values of the two variables for that observation. Scatter plots are commonly used to identify patterns and trends in the data, as well as to detect outliers and anomalies.

  • hexbin plot, on the other hand, is similar to a scatter plot but uses hexagons instead of points to represent the data. The hexagons are colored according to the number of observations that fall within each hexagon, with darker colors indicating higher densities of points. Hexbin plots are useful when dealing with large datasets, as they can help to visualize the overall distribution of the data more clearly than scatter plots.

Preprocessing the dataset¶

Solving the problem of missing values

  1. Drop columns that have missing values: In this case, we lose one of the features that may contain useful values if this problem is solved. So, if the number of these lost data is not very high, it does not seem to be a suitable method.

  2. Fill in the blanks with stats (like mode): By doing this, the variance of the data will be disturbed and also, the general distribution of the data may be disturbed, which is not desirable.

  3. Drop rows that contain missing values: By deleting the data, the distribution of other features may be disturbed. So, like the first case, it is not a good thing.

  4. Filling blank values with average data in the column (for numeric columns): It has the same problem as the second method.

  5. Filling the blank values with the most repeated data in the column: It has the same problem as the second method.

  6. Using predictive algorithm to predict missing values: It means creating a predictive model to estimate values that will substitute the missing data. In this case, we divide our data set into two sets: One set with no missing values for the variable and another one with missing values. We then use the set with no missing values to create a model that will predict the missing values in the other set. There are several techniques for imputation using predictive algorithms such as:

    • K-nearest neighbor (KNN) algorithm
    • Random Forest
    • Neural Networks
    • Decision Trees

At first, it is necessary to replace the values that are wrong with the NaN. For this purpose, according to my research, I will describe each of the features in the dataset.

  1. Unnamed: 0.2, Unnamed: 0.1, Unnamed: 0: It seems they don't contain any useful information.
  2. id: A unique identifier for each house in the dataset.
  3. date: The date that the house was sold.
  4. price: The sale price of the house.
  5. bedrooms: The number of bedrooms in the house.
  6. bathrooms: The number of bathrooms in the house.
  7. sqft_living: The total living area of the house in square feet.
  8. sqft_lot: The total lot area of the house in square feet.
  9. floors: The number of floors in the house.
  10. waterfront: A binary variable indicating whether the house has a waterfront view (1) or not (0).
  11. view: A rating of the house's view, on a scale of 0-4.
  12. condition: A rating of the house's overall condition, on a scale of 1-5.
  13. grade: A rating of the house's overall construction quality, on a scale of 1-13.
  14. sqft_above: The living area of the house above ground level, in square feet.
  15. sqft_basement: The living area of the house below ground level, in square feet.
  16. yr_built: The year that the house was built.
  17. yr_renovated: The year that the house was last renovated.
  18. zipcode: The zipcode of the area where the house is located.
  19. lat: The latitude of the house's location.
  20. long: The longitude of the house's location.
  21. sqft_living15: The average living area of the 15 nearest houses in the dataset, in square feet.
  22. sqft_lot15: The average lot area of the 15 nearest houses in the dataset, in square feet.
  23. location: The location of the house, possibly as a text string.
  24. style: The architectural style of the house, possibly as a text string.
  25. house_age: The age of the house in years.

In this way, for numeric columns, we can replace data that does not conform to the specified format.

In [102]:
df.isna().sum()

df.loc[df['price'] <= 0, 'price'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['bedrooms'] < 0, 'bedrooms'] = np.nan

df['bathrooms'] = df['bathrooms'].round()
df.loc[df['bathrooms'] < 0, 'bathrooms'] = np.nan

df.loc[df['sqft_living'] <= 0, 'sqft_living'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['sqft_lot'] <= 0, 'sqft_lot'] = np.nan
# df.loc[(df['floors'] <= 0) | (~df['floors'].astype(int).eq(df['floors'])), 'floors'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['floors'] <= 0, 'floors'] = np.nan
df.loc[~df['waterfront'].between(0, 1), 'waterfront'] = np.nan
df.loc[~df['view'].between(0, 4), 'view'] = np.nan
df.loc[~df['condition'].between(1, 5), 'condition'] = np.nan
df.loc[~df['grade'].between(1, 13), 'grade'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['sqft_above'] <= 0, 'sqft_above'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['sqft_basement'] < 0, 'sqft_basement'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['yr_built'] < 0, 'yr_built'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['yr_renovated'] < 0, 'yr_renovated'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['sqft_living15'] <= 0, 'sqft_living15'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['sqft_lot15'] <= 0, 'sqft_lot15'] = np.nan
df.loc[df['house_age'] < 0, 'house_age'] = np.nan

For categorical features, which are usually stored as string or object in data frame, what preprocessings are useful? Are these methods necessary for all of these columns?

For categorical features stored as strings or objects in a data frame, there are several preprocessing methods that can be useful, including:

  1. Label Encoding: This method assigns a unique numerical label to each category in the column, thereby converting the categorical data into numerical data that can be used by machine learning algorithms. However, it is important to note that label encoding does not create any ranking or order of the categories, and therefore may not be appropriate for all categorical features.

  2. One-Hot Encoding: This method creates a new binary column for each category in the original column. Each row in the new columns is assigned a value of 1 if the corresponding category is present in the original column, and 0 otherwise. One-hot encoding is useful when there are multiple categories in a column and there is no natural ordering or ranking among them.

  3. Binary Encoding: This method is similar to one-hot encoding, but instead of creating a new column for each category, it creates a binary representation of the category using the existing columns. This can help reduce the dimensionality of the dataset and improve the efficiency of the machine learning algorithms.

  4. Frequency Encoding: This method replaces each category with its frequency or count in the dataset. This can be useful when there are a large number of categories in a column and one-hot encoding would result in a high-dimensional feature space.

The choice of preprocessing method for categorical features depends on the specific characteristics of the data and the problem at hand. Not all preprocessing methods are necessary for all categorical columns, and it is important to carefully consider the impact of each method on the analysis and prediction. For example, label encoding may be appropriate for categorical features that have a natural ordering or ranking, while one-hot encoding may be more appropriate for features with multiple categories and no natural ordering. Similarly, binary encoding may be useful for high-dimensional data, while frequency encoding may be appropriate for features with a large number of categories.

Is it possible to drop some columns? Why?

Yes, it is possible to drop some columns from a dataset. There are several reasons why we might want to drop columns:

  1. Reducing Dimensionality: Removing columns can help simplify the dataset and reduce its dimensionality. This can be particularly useful when dealing with large datasets or when the model is computationally expensive.

  2. Irrelevant or Redundant Information: Some columns may contain irrelevant or redundant information that does not contribute to the analysis or prediction. Dropping these columns can help improve the accuracy of the model by reducing noise and focusing on relevant information.

  3. Missing or Incomplete Data: Some columns may have a large number of missing or incomplete data points. In such cases, dropping these columns can help avoid bias and ensure that the model is trained on complete data.

However, it is important to be cautious when dropping columns and to carefully consider the impact on the model and the analysis. Dropping important columns can lead to loss of valuable information and potentially impact the accuracy of the model. Therefore, it is important to carefully analyze the dataset and determine which columns can be safely dropped without affecting the quality of the analysis or prediction.

What is the purpose of normalizing and standardizing in numerical features? Is there a need to do this in this project?

The purpose of normalizing and standardizing numerical features in a dataset is to ensure that each feature is on a similar scale and has a similar range of values. This can be important for machine learning algorithms that use distance-based calculations, such as k-nearest neighbors (k-NN) and support vector machines (SVM).Normalization and standardization are both methods of scaling the data, but they differ in the way they adjust the values of the features:

  • Normalization: This method scales the data so that it ranges from 0 to 1. It is calculated by subtracting the minimum value of the feature and dividing by the range (i.e., the difference between the maximum and minimum values).

  • Standardization: This method scales the data so that it has a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. It is calculated by subtracting the mean of the feature and dividing by the standard deviation.

Normalization and standardization can improve the performance of machine learning algorithms by Reducing the impact of outliers, Improving convergence, and Improving the accuracy of models.

Improving the accuracy of models: Scaling the data can help machine learning algorithms better distinguish between features that are important and those that are less important.

The choice of normalization or standardization method depends on the specific characteristics of the data and the machine learning algorithm being used. In general, normalization is useful when the feature values have a clear minimum and maximum range, while standardization is useful when the feature values are not bounded and have a Gaussian-like distribution.

To train and finally evaluate the machine learning model, it is necessary to divide the data into two groups, training and testing. What is the ratio of this division? What are the ways to divide and build these two categories?

The ratio of dividing data into training and testing sets can vary depending on the size of the dataset and the complexity of the model. However, a commonly used ratio is 70:30 or 80:20, where 70% or 80% of the data is used for training the model and the remaining 30% or 20% is used for testing the model.

There are several ways to divide the data into training and testing sets:

  1. Simple Hold-Out Method: In this method, the dataset is randomly split into two sets, one for training the model and the other for testing the model. This method is simple but may result in biased estimates if the dataset is not representative of the population.

  2. K-Fold Cross-Validation: In this method, the dataset is divided into K equal-sized subsets, with K-1 subsets used for training the model and the remaining subset used for testing the model. This process is repeated K times, with each subset serving as the testing set once. This method is more robust than the simple hold-out method and can provide a more accurate estimate of model performance.

  3. Stratified Sampling: In some cases, the dataset may not be evenly distributed across all classes or categories. In such cases, stratified sampling can be used to ensure that the training and testing datasets are representative of the population. In this method, the dataset is divided into strata or subgroups based on a specific attribute, and the training and testing sets are created by sampling from each stratum.

  4. Time-Based Splitting: In some cases, the data may have a temporal or time-based component. In such cases, it is important to split the data into training and testing sets based on time. The training set should contain data from earlier time periods, while the testing set should contain data from later time periods. This method ensures that the model is evaluated on data that it has not seen before.

Overall, the choice of splitting method depends on the specific characteristics of the dataset and the problem at hand. A well-designed split can help ensure that the model is accurately trained and evaluated, leading to better predictions and insights.

Sometimes, in addition to the two categories of training and testing, we also have another category. Explain about this category (validation).

In addition to the training and testing datasets, it is common to also have a third category known as the validation dataset. The validation dataset is used to evaluate the performance of the model during the training process and to tune the model's hyperparameters.

During the training process, the model is typically trained on the training dataset and evaluated on the validation dataset after each epoch or iteration. This allows us to monitor the model's performance and adjust the hyperparameters to improve the model's accuracy. The validation dataset is used to prevent overfitting, which occurs when the model becomes too complex and fits too closely to the training data, resulting in poor performance on new or unseen data.

The validation dataset is different from the testing dataset in that it is not used to evaluate the final performance of the model. Instead, the testing dataset is used to evaluate the performance of the model after it has been fully trained and fine-tuned on the training and validation datasets. The testing dataset provides an unbiased estimate of the model's performance on new or unseen data.

Overall, the use of a validation dataset is an important step in the machine learning process. It allows us to fine-tune the model's hyperparameters and prevent overfitting, leading to a more accurate and robust model.

Training, evaluation and regulation¶

1. Linear Regression¶

Main form of simple linear regression function: $$f(x) = \alpha x + \beta$$

here we want to find the intercept($\alpha$) and slope($\beta$) by minimizing the derivation of the RSS function:

  • step 1: Compute RSS of the training data
$$ RSS = \Sigma (y_i - (\hat{\beta} + \hat{\alpha} * x_i) )^2 $$
  • step 2: Compute the derivatives of the RSS function in term of $\underline{\alpha}$ and $\underline{\beta}$, and set them equal to 0 to find the desired parameters
$$ \frac{\partial RSS}{\partial \beta} = \Sigma (-f(x_i) + \hat{\beta} + \hat{\alpha} * x_i) = 0$$$$ \to \hat{\beta} = \hat{y} - \hat{\alpha} \hat{x} \to (1)$$$$ \frac{\partial RSS}{\partial \alpha} = \Sigma (-2 x_i y_i + 2 \hat{\beta} x_i + 2\hat{\alpha} x_i ^ 2) = 0 \to (2)$$$$ (1) , (2) \to \hat{\alpha} = \frac{\Sigma{(x_i - \hat{x})(y_i - \hat{y})}}{\Sigma{(x_i - \hat{x})^2}} $$

$$ \hat{\beta} = \hat{y} - \hat{\alpha} \hat{x}$$

Based on the formula above, we write this function to compute the parameters of a simple linear regression.

In [111]:
def simple_linear_regression(input_feature, output):
    n = len(input_feature)
    
    # compute the sum of input_feature and output, and the averages
    sum_xi = sum(input_feature)
    sum_yi = sum(output)
    
    avg_x = sum_xi/n
    avg_y = sum_yi/n
    
    # compute the product of difference between the output and average of 
    # it and differnce between input_feature and the average, and its sum
    x_y = sum((input_feature - avg_x)*(output - avg_y))
    
    # compute the squared value of the input_feature and its sum
    x_2 = sum((input_feature - avg_x)**2)
    
    # use the formula for the slope
    intercept = x_y/x_2
    
    # use the formula for the intercept
    slope = avg_y - (intercept*avg_x)
    
    return (intercept, slope)

And this function, which predicts the value of given data based on the calculated intercept and slope.

def get_regression_predictions(input_feature, intercept, slope):
    # calculate the predicted values
    predicted_values = (intercept*input_feature + slope)

    return (predicted_values)

Now that we have a model and can make predictions let's evaluate our model using Root Mean Square Error (RSME). RMSE is the square root of the mean of the squared differences between the residuals and the residuals is just a fancy word for the difference between the predicted output and the true output.

The following function computes the RSME of a simple linear regression model given the input_feature, output, intercept and slope.

In [113]:
import math

def get_root_mean_square_error(predicted_values , output):
    n = len(predicted_values)

    # Compute the residuals (since we are squaring it doesn't matter which order you subtract)
    residuals = predicted_values - output

    # square the residuals and add them up
    sum_residuals2 = sum(residuals**2)

    # find the mean of the above phrase
    mean_residuals2 = sum_residuals2/n
   
    # calculate the root
    RMSE = math.sqrt(mean_residuals2)

    return(RMSE)

The RMSE has no bound and it is not easy to find out the percentage of fitting the model into data with it. instead, we use R2 score. The R2 score is calculated by comparing the sum of the squared differences between the actual and predicted values of the dependent variable to the total sum of squared differences between the actual and mean values of the dependent variable. Matematically, the R2 score formula is shown as follows:

$$R^2 = 1 - \frac{SSres}{SStot} = 1 - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{i,true} - y_{i,pred})^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{i,true} - \bar{y}_{true})^2} $$

The following function calculates the R2 score of a given input_feature, output, intercept, and slope:

In [114]:
def get_r2_score(predicted_values, output):
    n = len(predicted_values)

    # then compute the residuals (since we are squaring it doesn't matter which order you subtract)
    residuals = output - predicted_values
    
    # square the residuals and add them up -> SSres
    SSres = sum(residuals**2)
    
    # compute the SStot
    avg_output = sum(output)/n
    SStot = sum((output - avg_output)**2)

    # compute the R2 score value
    R2_score = 1 - (SSres/SStot)

    return(R2_score)

In regression analysis, several performance metrics are used to evaluate the accuracy of the prediction model. Four commonly used metrics are:

Residual Sum of Squares (RSS): The RSS is a measure of the difference between the predicted and actual values of the dependent variable. It is used to assess how well a regression model fits the data. A lower RSS indicates a better fit of the model to the data. However, RSS alone does not provide a sense of the scale of the error, since it depends on the number of observations in the dataset. Therefore, it is often normalized by dividing it by the number of degrees of freedom in the model to obtain the mean square error (MSE). Mathematically, RSS is defined as:

$$RSS = (y - )^2$$

where $y$ is the actual value of the dependent variable, $$ is the predicted value of the dependent variable, and is the sum over all the observations in the dataset.

Mean Squared Error (MSE): The MSE is the average of the squared differences between the predicted and actual values of the dependent variable. It provides a measure of the magnitude of the error, and is useful for comparing the performance of different models. A smaller MSE indicates a better fit of the model to the data. Mathematically, MSE is defined as:

$$MSE = \frac{RSS}{n}$$

where $n$ is the number of observations in the dataset.

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): The RMSE is the square root of the MSE. It provides a measure of the average magnitude of the error in the same units as the dependent variable. The RMSE is often used in practice because it is easier to interpret than the MSE. Mathematically, RMSE is defined as:

$$RMSE = \sqrt{MSE}$$

R-squared (R2) Score: The R2 score is a measure of how well a regression model fits the data. It is the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variable. A higher R2 score indicates a better fit of the model to the data. The R2 score can be interpreted as the percentage of the total variation in the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variable. However, the R2 score has some limitations. For example, it can be biased towards models with more independent variables, and it does not provide information about the precision of the estimates. Mathematically, R2 score is defined as:

$$R2 = 1 - \frac{RSS}{TSS}$$

where $TSS$ is the total sum of squares, which is the sum of the squared differences between the actual values and the mean value of the dependent variable. R2 score ranges from 0 to 1, where 0 indicates that the model does not explain any of the variability in the dependent variable, and 1 indicates that the model explains all of the variability in the dependent variable.

As You see, the confussion matrix is typically organized into rows and columns, where each row represents the predicted class labels and each column represents the actual class labels.

The four cells of the confusion matrix represent the number of instances that fall into each of the following categories:

  • True positives (TP): The number of instances that are correctly predicted as positive (belonging to the positive class).
  • False positives (FP): The number of instances that are incorrectly predicted as positive (belonging to the negative class, but predicted as positive).
  • False negatives (FN): The number of instances that are incorrectly predicted as negative (belonging to the positive class, but predicted as negative).
  • True negatives (TN): The number of instances that are correctly predicted as negative (belonging to the negative class).

The accuracy of a classification model is defined as the proportion of correctly predicted instances (TP and TN) out of the total number of instances (TP, TN, FP, and FN). The formula for accuracy is:

$$Accuracy = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + TN + FP + FN} = \frac{1869 + 1842}{1869 + 318 + 294 + 1842} = 0.8584$$

This formula counts the number of instances that are correctly classified (TP and TN) and divides it by the total number of instances in the dataset. The resulting value is a percentage that represents the overall accuracy of the model in predicting the correct class label.

You can see the calculated accuracy here, is equal to the output of function accuracy_score, which I've printed.

Overfitting and underfitting are common problems in machine learning that can affect the performance of predictive models.

  • Overfitting occurs when a model is too complex and fits the training data too closely, to the point that it captures the noise or random fluctuations in the data rather than the underlying patterns. An overfit model may have high accuracy on the training data but poor generalization performance on new, unseen data. This is because the model has essentially memorized the training data and cannot generalize to new examples that are different from the training data. Overfitting can be caused by a wide range of factors, such as using a model that is too complex, using too many features, or not having enough data for the complexity of the model.

  • Underfitting occurs when a model is too simple and cannot capture the underlying patterns in the data. An underfit model may have poor accuracy on both the training data and new, unseen data, because it is not able to capture the important features of the data. Underfitting can be caused by using a model that is too simple, not using enough features, or not having enough data for the complexity of the model.

The goal of machine learning is to find a model that can generalize well to new, unseen data. To achieve this, it is important to find the right balance between model complexity and the amount of data available. A model that is too complex may overfit the data, while a model that is too simple may underfit the data. One way to address overfitting is to use regularization techniques, such as L1 or L2 regularization, which add a penalty term to the loss function to discourage overly complex models. Another way to address overfitting is to use techniques such as cross-validation or early stopping to monitor the model performance on new, unseen data during training. To address underfitting, it may be necessary to use a more complex model or to gather more data to better capture the underlying patterns in the data.

In order to see whether overfitting or underfitting has occurred, we obtain and compare the accuracy of the models on both training and test data.

here is a list of all the hyperparameters available in scikit-learn's implementation of the random forest classifier:

  • n_estimators: The number of decision trees in the forest.
  • criterion: The function used to measure the quality of a split.
  • max_depth: The maximum depth of each decision tree.
  • min_samples_split: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
  • min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node.
  • min_weight_fraction_leaf: The minimum weighted fraction of the sum total of weights required to be at a leaf node.
  • max_features: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split.
  • max_leaf_nodes: The maximum number of leaf nodes in each decision tree.
  • min_impurity_decrease: The minimum impurity decrease required to split an internal node.
  • bootstrap: Whether bootstrap samples are used when building decision trees.
  • oob_score: Whether to use out-of-bag samples to estimate the generalization accuracy.
  • n_jobs: The number of jobs to run in parallel for both fit and predict.
  • random_state: The random number generator seed used for random sampling of the training data.
  • verbose: Controls the verbosity when fitting and predicting.
  • warm_start: Whether to reuse the solution of the previous call to fit and add more estimators to the ensemble.

More details for n_estimators and max_features:

  • n_estimators: This hyperparameter controls the number of decision trees in the random forest. Increasing the number of trees can lead to better performance, but also increases the computational cost and potential overfitting. The default value for this hyperparameter is 100, but it can be tuned based on the dataset and desired performance.
  • max_features: This hyperparameter controls the number of features randomly selected at each split of a decision tree. The default value for classification tasks is "sqrt", which means the square root of the total number of features is used. Increasing this value can lead to more complex models with potentially better performance, but also increases the risk of overfitting. On the other hand, decreasing this value can lead to simpler models that are less prone to overfitting but may have lower performance.

What are variance and bias, and the relation?

  • Bias refers to the error that is introduced by approximating a real-world problem with a simpler model. A model with high bias tends to make strong assumptions about the data and may underfit the data. In other words, it is unable to capture the true underlying patterns in the data. High bias models are often too simple and lack the complexity needed to accurately model the data.

  • Variance, on the other hand, refers to the error that is introduced by the model's sensitivity to small fluctuations or noise in the training data. A model with high variance tends to overfit the data, meaning that it fits the training data too closely and is unable to generalize well to new, unseen data. In other words, the model is too complex and captures both the signal and the noise in the data.

The relationship between bias and variance can be visualized using the bias-variance tradeoff. The tradeoff arises because increasing the complexity of a model (i.e., adding more parameters or increasing the size of the model) can reduce bias but increase variance, while decreasing the complexity of a model can reduce variance but increase bias.

The goal, is to find a balance between bias and variance that minimizes the overall error, which is known as the generalization error. A model that is too simple (i.e., high bias) will have a high error on both the training and testing data, while a model that is too complex (i.e., high variance) will have a low error on the training data but a high error on the testing data. The optimal model is one that has low bias and low variance, which means that it can accurately model the underlying patterns in the data without overfitting.

Does dicision tree performs better, or random forest in terms of variance and bias?

Random forests tend to perform better than decision trees in terms of variance and bias. While decision trees can be prone to high variance and bias, random forests are designed to reduce these issues by combining multiple decision trees and taking a random subset of features and data samples for each tree. Random forests are designed to reduce the variance and overfitting that can occur in decision trees.

Gradient-boosting¶

What is Gradient-boosting?

Gradient Boosting is a machine learning technique used for building predictive models, especially in the context of regression and classification problems. It works by combining multiple weak learners (i.e., models that perform slightly better than random guessing) to create a strong learner (i.e., a model that performs well on the given task).

The general idea behind Gradient Boosting is to iteratively add new models to the ensemble, where each model is trained to correct the errors of the previous models. Specifically, the algorithm works as follows:

  1. Initialize the ensemble with a simple model, such as a decision tree with only one split.

  2. Train the model to predict the target variable.

  3. Calculate the residuals (i.e., the differences between the predicted values and the actual values) for each observation in the training data.

  4. Fit a new model to the residuals, with the goal of predicting the residuals more accurately than the previous model.

  5. Add the new model to the ensemble, and update the predictions by adding the predictions of the new model multiplied by a learning rate (which controls the contribution of each model to the ensemble).

  6. Repeat steps 3-5 until the ensemble reaches a desired level of performance, or until a stopping criterion is met.

The key idea behind Gradient Boosting is to use the gradient of the loss function with respect to the predictions of the previous models (i.e., the residuals) as a guide for fitting the new model. This allows the algorithm to focus on the areas where the previous models performed poorly, and to gradually improve the overall performance of the ensemble. Gradient Boosting is a powerful and flexible technique that can be used for a wide range of machine learning tasks. It has been shown to perform well on many benchmark datasets, and is widely used in industry and academia for building predictive models.

What is difference between boosting tree and decision tree?

Boosting and decision trees are two different concepts in machine learning, but they are often used together in the context of ensemble learning.

  • Boosting is a general technique for improving the performance of machine learning algorithms by combining multiple weak learners into a single strong learner. The idea is to iteratively train new models that focus on the examples that were misclassified by the previous models, and to combine the predictions of all the models into a final prediction. Boosting can be used with many different types of weak learners, including decision trees.

  • Decision trees, on the other hand, are a specific type of machine learning algorithm that can be used for both regression and classification problems. A decision tree is essentially a flowchart-like structure that recursively partitions the data into smaller subsets based on the values of the input variables. Each internal node of the tree represents a test on a single input variable, and each leaf node represents a prediction for the target variable.

The main difference between boosting and decision trees is that boosting is a technique for improving the performance of machine learning algorithms, while decision trees are a specific type of algorithm. Decision trees can be used as weak learners in boosting, but boosting can also be used with other types of weak learners, such as neural networks or support vector machines.

What is XGBoost?

XGBoost (eXtreme Gradient Boosting) is a popular implementation of the Gradient Boosting algorithm that is optimized for performance and scalability. It is widely used in industry and academia for a wide range of machine learning tasks, including regression, classification, and ranking. XGBoost is a powerful and flexible algorithm that can be used for a wide range of machine learning tasks. Its speed, accuracy, and scalability make it a popular choice in many applications, including recommendation systems, fraud detection, and image classification.

The basic idea behind XGBoost is similar to other Gradient Boosting algorithms, but it includes several key optimizations that make it faster and more accurate. Here are the main steps of the XGBoost algorithm:

  1. Initialize the model: XGBoost starts with a single decision tree with a single leaf node, which represents the mean of the target variable.

  2. Calculate the gradients and hessians: For each observation in the training data, XGBoost calculates the gradient and hessian of the loss function with respect to the predicted value. The gradient is the derivative of the loss function, and the hessian is the second derivative.

  3. Build a tree to fit the residuals: XGBoost builds a decision tree to fit the residuals (i.e., the differences between the predicted values and the actual values). The tree is built using a greedy algorithm that recursively splits the data into subsets based on the values of the input variables.

  4. Add the tree to the model: XGBoost adds the new tree to the model, and updates the predictions by adding the predictions of the new tree multiplied by a learning rate (which controls the contribution of each tree to the model).

  5. Repeat steps 2-4 until the model reaches a desired level of performance, or until a stopping criterion is met.

In addition to these basic steps, XGBoost includes several key optimizations, such as:

  • Regularization: XGBoost includes several types of regularization, such as L1 and L2 regularization, to prevent overfitting and improve generalization performance.

  • Parallel processing: XGBoost uses parallel processing to speed up the training process, by splitting the data and the computations across multiple cores or nodes.

  • Tree pruning: XGBoost prunes the decision trees to remove unnecessary branches and reduce the complexity of the model, which improves both speed and accuracy.
